TikTok hides nasty videos from users
According to TikTok, the number of its users in the world exceeds 500 million, 40% of whom are under the age of 18.
Imagine China / Reuters
Chinese social network TikTok censors videos that mention Tiananmen Square, Tibet’s independence, or the banned religious group Falun Gong, The Guardian reports.
According to documents obtained by the publication, the owner of TikTok (ByteDance) is using the app to promote China’s foreign policy goals abroad.
Most of the violations related to China's policy fall under the "inflammation of hatred."
In each case, TikTok places objectionable posts in a context appropriate to the general rules, so that the actions of the social network do not look censored.
For example, the ban on criticism of China’s socialist system is subject to a general ban on “criticism or attacks on the policies and social rules of any country, such as the constitutional monarchy, the parliamentary system, etc.”
The ban on mentioning incidents on Tiananmen Square or the genocide in Cambodia falls under the "distortion of the history of China or other countries".
The document also lists outlawed names of twenty “foreign leaders or statesmen,” including the presidents of North Korea, Kim Jong-un, Kim Il-sung and Kim Jong-un, Indian politician Mahatma Gandhi, U.S. presidents Donald Trump and Barack Obama, and Japan’s presidents, Indra Nakhon.
The prohibited material is divided into two categories, as stated in the document.
Posts from the first category are deleted by the administrators of the social network and may result in blocking of the user.
Not too strict violations belong to the second category: such publications remain on the site, but their distribution is limited by TikTok algorithms.
ByteDance told The Guardian that these rules are outdated and no longer applied: “We are now using a localized approach to moderation, and we are also attracting independent local experts.”
Russian users of TikTok have no specific restrictions on publication, says the co-founder of the “Production Center” Rustem Bogdanov.
“Production Center” is one of the Russian media companies that officially cooperates with TikTok.
All advertising materials of bloggers "Production Center" agrees with the representatives of the social network, but user materials can be placed without agreement, Bogdanov reports.
When asked whether TikTok can speak about politics or Putin, Bogdanov responded positively and said that he had seen such publications.
Bogdanov agrees with the founder of Our Didgital agency Roman Zaripov: "The basic rules for users TikTok lists in the user agreement: you can not post shocking content, discriminatory statements, and so on."
But under these rules you can submit any content that the moderators do not like, notes Zaripov.
Zaripova Agency is another Russian partner of TikTok.
According to TikTok, the number of its users in the world exceeds 500 million, 40% of whom are under the age of 18.
By user agreement, only persons over the age of 13 can use TikTok.
Social network administrators check their age using artificial intelligence: the neural network analyzes faces and determines how old a person looks, Bogdanov says.
If the neural network decides that the user is younger, his account can be deleted, he adds.
According to RBC, in September 2019, ByteDance opened an office in Moscow on the territory of WeWork coworking.
